               <interp inst="t18410823-2271" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18410823"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18410823-2271" type="date" value="18410823"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18410823-2271-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2271-18410823 t18410823-2271-offence-1 t18410823-2271-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2271. <persName id="def1-2271-18410823" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2271-18410823" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2271-18410823" type="age" value="24"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2271-18410823" type="surname" value="WALTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2271-18410823" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOSEPH WALTON</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18410823-2271-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18410823-2271-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18410823-2271-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp> for unlawfully, maliciously, and feloniously assaulting <persName id="t18410823-name-1512" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1512" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1512" type="surname" value="AXON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1512" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18410823-2271-offence-1 t18410823-name-1512"></join>Joseph Axon</persName>, on the <rs id="t18410823-cd-273" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18410823-2271-offence-1 t18410823-cd-273"></join>2nd of July</rs>, and stabbing and wounding him, in and upon the right thigh, with intent to do him some grievous bodily harm.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RYLAND</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410823-name-1513" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1513" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1513" type="surname" value="AXON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1513" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH AXON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pork-butcher, and live at Romford, in Essex. On the 2nd of July I was at Fairlop fair—I was returning with my brother Thomas, about a quarter-past ten o'clock in the evening, and when we got about a quarter of a mile from the fair I saw a small party collected toge<lb></lb>ther, fighting—a person named Cutts was stripped, ready to fight—I spoke him, and after I spoke to him he went on fighting with the prisoner—they both fell, and when they were down the prisoner's wife came and kicked Cutts—I said it was unfair, and my brother went and took the pri<lb></lb>soner's wife away, picked the prisoner up, and afterwards picked up Cutts—the prisoner immediately came to me, and stabbed me twice in the back Part of my thigh, with some sharp instrument—I felt the blow, and felt</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184108230196"></xptr>
               <p>behind, and felt the blood in my trowsers—I had not interfered in the fight at all—I he stab did not disable me at the time—about five minutes after the prisoner stabbed me, he came to me and hit me with his fist in the forehead—my brother came up, laid hold of him, and I did so also—I let him go—I sent for Mr. Bowers, a surgeon at Romford, as soon as I got home—I was obliged to go to bed, and it was five or six weeks before I was able to do any kind of work—I was under the doctor's care about that time—I was confined to my bed seven or eight days.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you dined to-day? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> That is my business—I have had my dinner, of course—I believe I have had a drop of porter—nothing else that I know of—I am quite sober—I had been in the fair about four or five hours, amusing myself—I had only been in one booth—my brother Thomas was with me—we had some bot<lb></lb>tled porter in the booth—I cannot say how much we had—it did me no harm—I left the booth sober—I cannot tell what we paid—I am certain I paid 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., but whether I paid more, I cannot say—it was a joint pay<lb></lb>ment, a club—I will swear my share did not come to 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I had my brother and sisters with me, and believe I paid more than most of them—I am not positive I did not pay 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., or 50<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I might have paid 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I do not believe I did—I am quite sure I did not pay 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—nor 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., but you speak to me in such a curious sort of way—my brother Thomas pulled the prisoner's wife away with his hands—he did not pull her petticoats up, to my knowledge—I will not swear about it—I saw him pull her away —I saw him catch hold of her shoulders, and pull her away—I will not swear he did not pull her petticoats up for the purpose of exposing her—I was looking on, and saw him pull her away quite decently—I do not know whether she was knocked down or not—I here were other people round—I saw my brother pull her away—whether she fell down, I cannot say—I did not see her petticoats pulled up—I will not swear they were not—there were people standing before me so as to prevent my seeing—I told my brother I was done for—I do not recollect saying "Pitch into him"—I will not swear I did not say so—I was acquainted with Cults—he was not one of the party drinking with us—I do not know how the quarrel arose—my brother had been in my company up to the quarrel, and did not know how it arose.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RYLAND</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you perfectly sober when this took place? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.—I did not interfere with the prisoner's wife at all—I did not see her knocked down, or her clothes disturbed—it was rather a dark evening, and being in the forest, made it still darker.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410823-name-1514" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1514" type="surname" value="AXON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1514" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS AXON</persName>
                  </hi>. I was returning with my brother from Fairlop-fair—we were quite sober—I have known Cutts some time—I saw him in our way home, fighting with the prisoner—Cutts called out to me, "Halloo, <hi rend="italic">Tom,</hi> is that you?"—I said, "Yes, <hi rend="italic">Jem,</hi> is that you?"—they went on fighting, and both fell—I he prisoner's wife kicked Cutts as he laid on the ground, and I then interfered—I went to take the prisoner off from Cutts, and his wife struck me—I <hi rend="italic">shoved</hi> her with my arm, and she fell—<hi rend="italic">It</hi> might be with my <hi rend="italic">shoving</hi> her back with my arm, I cannot say—she got up and struck me again—I did not ill-use her in any way—I saw the prisoner make two hits at my brother—I did not see any thing in his hand at the time—I laid hold of him, and so did my brother—my brother said something to me—I let go of the prisoner, and went to him—I ob<lb></lb>served that he had been stabbed in the thigh—his trowsers had a hole in</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184108230197"></xptr>
               <p>them, and blood likewise—I went for a doctor, who came and attended him—he was confined to his room eight or nine days—I saw the wound.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You were all very sober that night? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I am a labourer, and work for my father at jobbing, or any thing—he is a pork-butcher, and keeps a shop at Romford—I serve in the shop but very little—I work in the field sometimes, and sometimes in the shop—I do not get my living at fairs and races—we had only been in one booth that night—I he Crown and Anchor—I know Cutts from living close by—he is a gardener—I did not hear Cutts say, "I want to fight, but the b—r won't let me"—my brother and I had had a bottle of porter together—my sisters were with us—we had three bottles between us all—I here were six or seven of us—my brother, my two sisters, Carter, a horse-dealer, and myself—I cannot tell who paid for the drink—I did not—I believe Carter did—he stood treat—we found the fight going on as we were returning from the fair—I went up to them as, I saw Cutts lying down, and the prisoner holding him by the throat—I did not say, "Pitch into him, the b—," nor did I hear it said—my brother did not say so—he never interfered at all—I did not hear Cutts say, "I want to fight, but the b—won't let me"—he was standing up when I went by, and he called to me—he was afraid of getting killed, I pose—I was taking a walk at the fair—I had no pea and thimble—the prisoner's wife was stand<lb></lb>ing alongside when Cutts called out to me—I went up to take the prisoner off Cutts—I did not pull his wife's petticoats over her head—I did not pull her petticoats up at all, nor meddle with her, only by <hi rend="italic">shoving</hi> her away, as she was kicking Cutts—I did not take hold of her by her shoul<lb></lb>ders—that I swear—as I went to take the prisoner away she hit me, and I pushed her away—my arm came about her shoulder—I did not strike her with my fist—she fell—I did not take her by the shoulders before she fell—her petticoats did not go up at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RYLAND</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you do anything indecent to her clothes or any thing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not—I did not go up to interfere till Cutts was on the ground.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410823-name-1515" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1515" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1515" type="surname" value="BAILEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410823-name-1515" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES BAILEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I work as a gardener, at Romford. I was present and saw the best part of the fight between Cutts and the prisoner, and staid till it was over—after it was over I saw the prisoner go and strike Joseph Axon in the side two or three times, with a knife I pose, but I did not know it was a knife when he struck him—my brother John was there—I went up to the prisoner and asked if he had got a knife in his hand—he said, "Yes, and I mean to use it too"—I hat was after he had used it to the prosecutor—he had it in his hand—I did not see him put it any where—I saw the blade of a knife in his hand—that was about half a minute after I saw him strike Axon in the side—I afterwards saw Axon bleeding.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How far does Axon live from Fairlop-fair? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Between three and four miles—he walked home—I had not been along with Axon in the fair.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you notice when the prisoner's wife was thrown down? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I did not—I saw her pulled away, and it was almost immediately after that I saw the prisoner strike Axon.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18410823-2271-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
